# Interaction States üñ±Ô∏è

## :hover
Selects an element when you mouse over it.
```css
a:hover {
  color: orange;
}
```

## :active
Selects an element the moment it is clicked.
```css
button:active {
  background-color: red;
}
```

## :focus
Selects an element when it has focus (clicked or tabbed to).
```css
input:focus {
  background-color: yellow;
}
```

# Structural Classes üèóÔ∏è

Target elements based on their position in the HTML structure.

## :first-child
Selects every `<p>` element that is the first child of its parent.
```css
p:first-child {
  color: blue;
}
```

## :last-child
Selects the last child.

## :nth-child(n)
Selects the nth child (e.g., all even rows).
```css
tr:nth-child(even) {
  background-color: #f2f2f2;
}
tr:nth-child(3) {
  color: red;
}
```

# ::before and ::after ‚ú®

Insert content before or after an element's content.

Required property: `content`.

```css
h1::before {
  content: "üåü ";
}

p::after {
  content: " - Read more";
  color: blue;
}
```

Often used for icons, decorative shapes, or clearing floats.

# Text Pseudo-elements üî°

## ::first-letter
Styles the first letter of a block element.
```css
p::first-letter {
  font-size: 200%;
  color: #8A2BE2;
}
```

## ::first-line
Styles the first line of a block element.
```css
p::first-line {
  background-color: yellow;
}
```

# ::selection üñçÔ∏è

Matches the portion of an element that is selected by a user (highlighted text).

Only a few properties apply: color, background, cursor, and outline.

```css
::selection {
  color: red;
  background: yellow;
}
```

# The :not() Selector üö´

Selects every element that is NOT a specific element/selector.

```css
/* Style all p elements that do NOT have class="intro" */
p:not(.intro) {
  color: red;
}
```

Great for applying general styles and excluding special cases.
